docs.abstract: The pandemic and the movement for racial justice have tested corporate pledges to elevate social concerns alongside shareholder interests. A new study finds companies are failing to follow through.
docs.snippet: The pandemic and the movement for racial justice have tested corporate pledges to elevate social concerns alongside shareholder interests. A new study finds companies are failing to follow through.
docs.lead_paragraph: Marc Benioff, chief executive of the technology giant Salesforce, presents himself as an evangelist for stakeholder capitalism: the idea that companies must elevate the interests of workers, the environment and local communities alongside shareholders.

headline.main: Stakeholder Capitalism Gets a Report Card. It’s Not Good.

docs.abstract: The e-commerce giant had struggled to gain a foothold in a society that prefers to shop in person, with cash, but now Italians are hooked on online shopping.
docs.snippet: The e-commerce giant had struggled to gain a foothold in a society that prefers to shop in person, with cash, but now Italians are hooked on online shopping.
docs.lead_paragraph: NAPLES, Italy — Ludovica Tomaciello had never shopped on Amazon before being trapped at her parents’ house in March during Italy’s coronavirus lockdown. Bored one afternoon scrolling TikTok, she spotted hair scrunchies that she then tracked down and ordered on Amazon.

headline.main: Pasta, Wine and Inflatable Pools: How Amazon Conquered Italy in the Pandemic
headline.print_headline: How’d Amazon  Conquer Italy? Inflatable Pools, Pasta and Wine

byline.original: By Adam Satariano and Emma Bubola

docs.abstract: Forget about drones. Amazon delivered something just as innovative with nuts and bolts.
docs.snippet: Forget about drones. Amazon delivered something just as innovative with nuts and bolts.

docs.abstract: There will be many traps to fall into, so watch out.
docs.snippet: There will be many traps to fall into, so watch out.
docs.lead_paragraph: After a few months of delays because of the coronavirus pandemic, this year’s Amazon Prime Day is now set for Oct. 13 and 14, just six weeks before Black Friday. The timing will most likely set off a cascade of sales that will last through December, making it even more confusing when you’re trying to determine what’s truly a good value for your money as we all try to shore up our emergency savings.

headline.main: 5 Things to Avoid on Prime Day

docs.abstract: Away from the political drama of the TikTok deal, Walmart has been taking steps that are already changing the company and, by extension, the broader retail sector.
docs.snippet: Away from the political drama of the TikTok deal, Walmart has been taking steps that are already changing the company and, by extension, the broader retail sector.
docs.lead_paragraph: Walmart’s planned investment in TikTok is being called “transformative.” Another analyst predicted the deal could “redefine retail” across the industry. “It is a bigger-picture opportunity,” said Oliver Chen, a retail analyst at Cowen.

headline.main: Beyond TikTok, Walmart Looks to Transform
headline.print_headline: Walmart Is Transforming Itself and Retail
